WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:17.265 --> 00:00:19.140
NEIL GAIMAN: Thank you
so much for having us.

00:00:22.490 --> 00:00:27.170
It's always fun to do
these Google things.

00:00:27.170 --> 00:00:29.380
It's always
particular fun for me

00:00:29.380 --> 00:00:33.455
when I'm out at Mountain View
because my little boy-- who

00:00:33.455 --> 00:00:37.161
is not actually a little
boy, he's 6 foot 2 and 30,

00:00:37.161 --> 00:00:38.880
but in my head,
he's my little boy--

00:00:38.880 --> 00:00:43.400
is actually one of you,
which is terrifying.

00:00:48.050 --> 00:00:49.940
So, right.

00:00:49.940 --> 00:00:53.740
We figured out
the running order,

00:00:53.740 --> 00:00:59.130
and tossed dice to see who
goes first, and it's me.

00:01:02.320 --> 00:01:06.650
So I'm going to
begin with a poem,

00:01:06.650 --> 00:01:12.040
and it's about an
awful lot of things.

00:01:12.040 --> 00:01:14.740
I love the fact that
this poem is now--

00:01:14.740 --> 00:01:19.160
people send me messages on
Twitter saying that they read

00:01:19.160 --> 00:01:23.280
it at weddings, and
other people seem

00:01:23.280 --> 00:01:28.550
to regard it as a poem
about upset and ignorance.

00:01:28.550 --> 00:01:31.840
And I think, probably,
it's about a lot of things,

00:01:31.840 --> 00:01:36.826
including getting off
your phone some time.

00:01:36.826 --> 00:01:45.330
But it's called "The
Day The Saucers Came."

00:01:45.330 --> 00:01:49.890
That day the saucers
landed, hundreds of them,

00:01:49.890 --> 00:01:54.720
golden, silent, coming down from
the sky like great snowflakes.

00:01:54.720 --> 00:01:58.380
And the people of Earth stood
and stared as they descended,

00:01:58.380 --> 00:02:03.190
waiting, dry-mouthed to find
what waited inside for us,

00:02:03.190 --> 00:02:06.410
and none of us knowing if
we would be here tomorrow.

00:02:06.410 --> 00:02:12.010
But you didn't notice
it because that day,

00:02:12.010 --> 00:02:16.080
the day the saucers came, by
some coincidence was the day

00:02:16.080 --> 00:02:18.720
that the graves
gave up their dead

00:02:18.720 --> 00:02:22.140
and the zombies pushed up
through soft earth, or erupted,

00:02:22.140 --> 00:02:24.740
shambling and
dull-eyed, unstoppable,

00:02:24.740 --> 00:02:28.200
came towards us, the living,
and we screamed and ran.

00:02:28.200 --> 00:02:32.250
But you did not notice
this, because, on the saucer

00:02:32.250 --> 00:02:37.810
day, which was the zombie
day, it was Ragnarok also.

00:02:37.810 --> 00:02:39.403
And the television
screens showed us

00:02:39.403 --> 00:02:42.390
a ship built of dead men's
nails, a serpent, a wolf,

00:02:42.390 --> 00:02:44.280
all bigger than the
mind could hold,

00:02:44.280 --> 00:02:46.560
and the cameraman could
not get far enough away.

00:02:46.560 --> 00:02:49.410
And then the gods came out.

00:02:49.410 --> 00:02:53.720
But you did not see them
coming because, on the

00:02:53.720 --> 00:02:58.190
saucer-zombie-battling-gods day,
the floodgates broke and each

00:02:58.190 --> 00:03:01.890
of us was engulfed by genies
and sprites offering us wishes

00:03:01.890 --> 00:03:05.690
and wonders and eternities and
charm and cleverness and true,

00:03:05.690 --> 00:03:09.540
brave hearts and pots of gold,
while giants feefofummed across

00:03:09.540 --> 00:03:12.890
the land, and killer bees.

00:03:12.890 --> 00:03:16.120
But you had no idea
of any of this,

00:03:16.120 --> 00:03:20.140
because that day, the
saucer day, the zombie day,

00:03:20.140 --> 00:03:22.540
the Ragnarok and fairies
day, the day the great winds

00:03:22.540 --> 00:03:25.150
came, and snows, and the
cities turned to crystal,

00:03:25.150 --> 00:03:28.420
the day all plants died,
plastics dissolved,

00:03:28.420 --> 00:03:31.340
the day the computers turned,
the screens telling us we

00:03:31.340 --> 00:03:34.080
would obey, the day
angels, drunk and muddled,

00:03:34.080 --> 00:03:36.515
stumbled from the bars and
all the bells of London

00:03:36.515 --> 00:03:39.950
were sounded, the day animals
spoke to us in Assyrian,

00:03:39.950 --> 00:03:43.250
the Yeti day, the
fluttering capes and arrival

00:03:43.250 --> 00:03:45.510
of the time machine day.

00:03:45.510 --> 00:03:47.930
You didn't notice any
of this because you

00:03:47.930 --> 00:03:50.580
were sitting in your room
not doing anything, not

00:03:50.580 --> 00:03:55.240
even reading, not really, just
looking at your telephone,

00:03:55.240 --> 00:03:56.760
wondering if I
was going to call.

00:04:07.980 --> 00:04:10.470
So, the next thing
that's going to happen

00:04:10.470 --> 00:04:11.980
is Amanda is going
to play a song.

00:04:11.980 --> 00:04:13.960
AMANDA PALMER: Yeah,
and you should intro it,

00:04:13.960 --> 00:04:16.550
but we should tell them
about the recording

00:04:16.550 --> 00:04:19.550
and why this all
happened, maybe.

00:04:19.550 --> 00:04:22.070
Or should we just
not bother with that?

00:04:22.070 --> 00:04:24.690
We made a record,
kind of by accident.

00:04:24.690 --> 00:04:26.440
We went on a tour and
decided to record it

00:04:26.440 --> 00:04:28.470
and that's what this record is.

00:04:28.470 --> 00:04:28.970
And--

00:04:28.970 --> 00:04:29.650
NEIL GAIMAN: Yeah,
there is a record

00:04:29.650 --> 00:04:31.983
called, "An Evening With Neil
Gaiman and Amanda Palmer."

00:04:31.983 --> 00:04:36.340
Three discs-- one of me,
one of her, one of us.

00:04:36.340 --> 00:04:37.890
And this is a song
that's actually

00:04:37.890 --> 00:04:40.980
on the "us" one, because
on the record I sing it,

00:04:40.980 --> 00:04:43.530
but Amanda's going to be
singing it now because--

00:04:43.530 --> 00:04:43.870
AMANDA PALMER: He's nervous!

00:04:43.870 --> 00:04:45.960
NEIL GAIMAN: She has a much,
much prettier voice than I do.

00:04:45.960 --> 00:04:47.918
AMANDA PALMER: I think
your voice is beautiful.

00:04:50.690 --> 00:04:52.740
NEIL GAIMAN: And it was
a song that, actually,

00:04:52.740 --> 00:04:55.300
is kind of relevant
to everybody here.

00:04:55.300 --> 00:05:00.890
And it began when I started
thinking about torch songs,

00:05:00.890 --> 00:05:04.450
because classic torch songs
are, basically, conversations

00:05:04.450 --> 00:05:08.000
that you have with a bartender
at 3 o'clock in the morning,

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:10.940
smoking a cigarette,
not wanting to go home

00:05:10.940 --> 00:05:12.980
with your heart broken.

00:05:12.980 --> 00:05:16.870
And I thought-- that
doesn't happen anymore.

00:05:16.870 --> 00:05:17.875
You can't smoke in bars.

00:05:20.790 --> 00:05:24.615
And if your heart
is broken, you're

00:05:24.615 --> 00:05:26.890
not going to be in a bar at
3 o'clock in the morning.

00:05:26.890 --> 00:05:28.931
You're going to be doing
something else entirely.

00:05:32.895 --> 00:05:34.520
[MUSIC - AMANDA
PALMER, "I GOOGLE YOU"]

00:09:02.095 --> 00:09:03.136
AMANDA PALMER: Thank you.

00:09:07.600 --> 00:09:13.110
So that song was
actually written by Neil,

00:09:13.110 --> 00:09:15.590
and I heard it in the best way.

00:09:15.590 --> 00:09:18.380
It was the first week that
we actually met and hung out.

00:09:18.380 --> 00:09:21.960
We weren't dating yet, this
was, like, five years ago.

00:09:21.960 --> 00:09:25.170
And he came to stay
at my house for a week

00:09:25.170 --> 00:09:28.850
while we were working on
this book project together.

00:09:28.850 --> 00:09:31.350
And I don't remember how it
came up, but we started chatting

00:09:31.350 --> 00:09:33.000
and he mentioned
that he'd written

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:36.830
a song for a cabaret
singer to sing,

00:09:36.830 --> 00:09:38.770
and I said, well,
just sing it for me.

00:09:38.770 --> 00:09:41.170
And he went, I
can't, I can't sing.

00:09:41.170 --> 00:09:46.720
And then he opened his mouth
and just sang it a cappella,

00:09:46.720 --> 00:09:49.470
and I couldn't believe what
a beautiful voice he had.

00:09:49.470 --> 00:09:52.768
And he's a pretty
clever writer, too.

00:09:55.760 --> 00:09:59.100
Anyway, so I put
some chords under it

00:09:59.100 --> 00:10:02.390
and that was sort of like
our first weird little thing

00:10:02.390 --> 00:10:04.000
that we did together.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:08.230
And I'm going to play
you one of mine now,

00:10:08.230 --> 00:10:10.506
and then Neil's going to read.

00:10:10.506 --> 00:10:12.880
I was thinking about maybe
taking requests from you guys,

00:10:12.880 --> 00:10:15.310
but I thought that that
might just get really weird.

00:10:15.310 --> 00:10:17.504
Because, also, I'm only
going to play one song.

00:10:17.504 --> 00:10:18.920
So I was just
standing back there,

00:10:18.920 --> 00:10:24.687
wondering what
would actually work.

00:10:24.687 --> 00:10:26.520
There's a song I was
practicing for the show

00:10:26.520 --> 00:10:28.350
tonight that I
think would be good.

00:10:28.350 --> 00:10:33.460
It might be a little sloppy,
but it's on the record

00:10:33.460 --> 00:10:37.050
so-- I thought that
would be relevant.

00:10:37.050 --> 00:10:39.060
And it's a song that
I wrote a couple years

00:10:39.060 --> 00:10:49.750
ago about all these
journalists asking me

00:10:49.750 --> 00:10:51.510
who my influences are.

00:10:51.510 --> 00:10:53.980
And especially-- I
get asked a lot, who

00:10:53.980 --> 00:10:55.580
are your female influences.

00:10:55.580 --> 00:10:57.580
And I realized I'd been
thinking about it really

00:10:57.580 --> 00:10:59.905
narrowly, and
especially the more you

00:10:59.905 --> 00:11:01.780
give the answer to the
question, you're like,

00:11:01.780 --> 00:11:03.934
OK-- Laurie Anderson,
and Madonna,

00:11:03.934 --> 00:11:05.350
and la di di di
di-- all this shit

00:11:05.350 --> 00:11:07.580
that I listened to
when I was a kid.

00:11:07.580 --> 00:11:12.530
And you start just having a
fucking laundry list of people.

00:11:12.530 --> 00:11:15.900
And it occurred to me, actually,
in the middle of the night

00:11:15.900 --> 00:11:20.160
one night, that I was
leaving out this giant one,

00:11:20.160 --> 00:11:23.440
and it struck me as
actually so important

00:11:23.440 --> 00:11:25.210
I decided to write
a song about it.

00:11:25.210 --> 00:11:26.216
So this is it.

