AMANDA PALMER: Thank you.

00:17:56.344 --> 00:17:58.260
NEIL GAIMAN: So at the
beginning of this year,

00:17:58.260 --> 00:18:05.500
I tried an experiment, with
BlackBerry sponsoring me.

00:18:05.500 --> 00:18:10.840
I went to Twitter, threw
out 12 questions on Twitter,

00:18:10.840 --> 00:18:16.060
and got hundreds and
thousands of replies back.

00:18:16.060 --> 00:18:21.240
And then picked the replies--
picked 12 replies pretty much

00:18:21.240 --> 00:18:25.940
at random, and used
them as yogurt starter

00:18:25.940 --> 00:18:29.300
for 12 short stories, one
for each month of the year.

00:18:29.300 --> 00:18:32.210
And I made a calendar of tales.

00:18:32.210 --> 00:18:35.420
And this is last month's tale.

00:18:40.610 --> 00:18:44.390
"That feels good," I said,
and I stretched my neck

00:18:44.390 --> 00:18:47.010
to get out the
last of the cramp.

00:18:47.010 --> 00:18:50.120
It didn't just feel good,
it felt great, actually.

00:18:50.120 --> 00:18:53.230
I'd been squashed up inside
that lamp for so long.

00:18:53.230 --> 00:18:57.060
You start to think that nobody's
ever going to run it again.

00:18:57.060 --> 00:18:59.150
"You're a genie,"
said the young lady

00:18:59.150 --> 00:19:01.430
with the polishing-cloth
in her hand.

00:19:01.430 --> 00:19:02.075
"I am.

00:19:02.075 --> 00:19:03.980
You're a smart girl, toots.

00:19:03.980 --> 00:19:08.230
What gave me away?" "The
arriving in a puff of smoke,"

00:19:08.230 --> 00:19:10.540
she said. "And you
look like a genie.

00:19:10.540 --> 00:19:13.860
You've got the turban
and the pointy shoes. "

00:19:13.860 --> 00:19:15.710
I folded my arms and blinked.

00:19:15.710 --> 00:19:18.180
Now I was wearing blue
jeans, gray sneakers,

00:19:18.180 --> 00:19:20.670
and a faded gray
sweater-- the male uniform

00:19:20.670 --> 00:19:22.920
of this time and this place.

00:19:22.920 --> 00:19:26.850
I raised my hand to my
forehead, and I bowed deeply.

00:19:26.850 --> 00:19:29.280
"I am the genie of the
lamp, " I told her.

00:19:29.280 --> 00:19:31.220
"Rejoice, O fortunate one.

00:19:31.220 --> 00:19:33.390
I have it in my power to
grant you three wishes.

00:19:33.390 --> 00:19:36.430
And don't try the 'wish for
more wishes' thing- I won't play

00:19:36.430 --> 00:19:37.870
and you'll lose a wish.

00:19:37.870 --> 00:19:38.640
Right.

00:19:38.640 --> 00:19:42.852
Go for it. " I
folded my arms again.

00:19:42.852 --> 00:19:45.310
"No," she said. "I mean thanks
and all that, but it's fine.

00:19:45.310 --> 00:19:48.920
I'm good." "Honey,"
I said. "Toots.

00:19:48.920 --> 00:19:49.720
Sweetie.

00:19:49.720 --> 00:19:50.800
Perhaps you misheard me.

00:19:50.800 --> 00:19:52.547
I'm a genie And
the three wishes?

00:19:52.547 --> 00:19:53.880
We're talking anything you want.

00:19:53.880 --> 00:19:55.004
You ever dreamed of flying?

00:19:55.004 --> 00:19:56.127
I can give you wings.

00:19:56.127 --> 00:19:57.960
You want to be wealthy,
richer than Croesus?

00:19:57.960 --> 00:19:58.720
You want power?

00:19:58.720 --> 00:19:59.570
Say it.

00:19:59.570 --> 00:20:00.300
Three wishes.

00:20:00.300 --> 00:20:02.430
Whatever you want."

00:20:02.430 --> 00:20:03.810
"Like I said,"
she said, "Thanks.

00:20:03.810 --> 00:20:05.880
I'm fine." "Would you
like something to drink?

00:20:05.880 --> 00:20:07.450
You must be parched
after spending

00:20:07.450 --> 00:20:09.500
so much time in that lamp.

00:20:09.500 --> 00:20:10.000
Wine?

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:10.530
Water?

00:20:10.530 --> 00:20:11.760
Tea?"

00:20:11.760 --> 00:20:12.760
"Uh..."

00:20:12.760 --> 00:20:16.420
Actually, now she came to
mention it, I was thirsty.

00:20:16.420 --> 00:20:19.230
"Do you have any mint tea?"

00:20:19.230 --> 00:20:21.120
She made me some mint
tea in a teapot that

00:20:21.120 --> 00:20:23.760
was almost a twin to the lamp
in which I'd spent the greater

00:20:23.760 --> 00:20:27.450
part of the last thousand years.

00:20:27.450 --> 00:20:32.750
"Thank you for the tea." "No
problem." "But I don't get it.

00:20:32.750 --> 00:20:36.270
Everyone I've ever met, they
start asking for things.

00:20:36.270 --> 00:20:37.230
A fancy house.

00:20:37.230 --> 00:20:39.580
A harem of gorgeous
women-- not that you'd

00:20:39.580 --> 00:20:41.280
want that, of course.

00:20:41.280 --> 00:20:43.780
"I might," she said.

00:20:43.780 --> 00:20:46.715
"You can't just make
assumptions about people.

00:20:46.715 --> 00:20:48.960
Oh, and don't call
me toots, or sweetie,

00:20:48.960 --> 00:20:50.190
or any of those things.

00:20:50.190 --> 00:20:51.904
My name's Hazel."

00:20:51.904 --> 00:20:53.110
"Ah!"

00:20:53.110 --> 00:20:54.060
I understood.

00:20:54.060 --> 00:20:55.640
"You want a
beautiful woman then?

00:20:55.640 --> 00:20:56.390
My apologies.

00:20:56.390 --> 00:20:58.790
You have but to wish."

00:20:58.790 --> 00:21:00.510
I folded my arms.

00:21:00.510 --> 00:21:02.110
"No," she said. "I'm good.

00:21:02.110 --> 00:21:02.620
No wishes.

00:21:02.620 --> 00:21:04.260
How's the tea?"

00:21:04.260 --> 00:21:08.720
I told her that the mint tea was
the finest I had ever tasted.

00:21:08.720 --> 00:21:11.030
She asked me when I'd
started feeling a need

00:21:11.030 --> 00:21:12.977
to grant people's
wishes, and whether I

00:21:12.977 --> 00:21:14.310
felt a desperate need to please.

00:21:18.930 --> 00:21:21.760
She asked about my
mother, and I told her

00:21:21.760 --> 00:21:24.190
that she could not judge me
as you would judge mortals,

00:21:24.190 --> 00:21:28.180
for I was a djinn, powerful and
wise, magical and mysterious.

00:21:28.180 --> 00:21:31.550
She asked me if I liked hummus,
and when I said that I did,

00:21:31.550 --> 00:21:33.410
she toasted a pita
bread and sliced it up

00:21:33.410 --> 00:21:37.010
for me to dip into the hummus.

00:21:37.010 --> 00:21:38.750
I dipped my bread
slices into the hummus

00:21:38.750 --> 00:21:40.910
and ate it with delight.

00:21:40.910 --> 00:21:42.870
The hummus gave me an idea.

00:21:42.870 --> 00:21:44.770
"Just make a wish,"
I said helpfully,

00:21:44.770 --> 00:21:47.460
"And I could have a meal fit
for a sultan brought in to you.

00:21:47.460 --> 00:21:49.500
Each dish would be finer
than the one before,

00:21:49.500 --> 00:21:52.310
and all served
upon golden plates.

00:21:52.310 --> 00:21:57.660
And you could keep the
plates afterwards."

00:21:57.660 --> 00:21:59.200
"It's good," she
said, with a smile.

00:21:59.200 --> 00:22:01.630
"Would you like
to go for a walk?"

00:22:01.630 --> 00:22:03.450
We walked together
through the town.

00:22:03.450 --> 00:22:06.110
It felt good to stretch my
legs after so many years

00:22:06.110 --> 00:22:07.410
in the lamp.

00:22:07.410 --> 00:22:11.010
We wound up in a public park,
sitting on a bench by a lake.

00:22:11.010 --> 00:22:14.680
It was warm, but gusty, and the
autumn leaves fell in flurries

00:22:14.680 --> 00:22:17.030
each time the wind blew.

00:22:17.030 --> 00:22:19.580
I told Hazel about
my youth as a djinn,

00:22:19.580 --> 00:22:21.719
of how we used to
eavesdrop on the angels

00:22:21.719 --> 00:22:23.260
and how they would
throw comets at as

00:22:23.260 --> 00:22:24.740
if they spied us listening.

00:22:24.740 --> 00:22:27.050
I told her of the bad
days of the djinn wars,

00:22:27.050 --> 00:22:29.170
and how King Suleiman
had imprisoned us

00:22:29.170 --> 00:22:31.430
inside hollow objects--
bottles, lamps,

00:22:31.430 --> 00:22:34.090
clay pots, that kind of thing.

00:22:34.090 --> 00:22:36.690
She told me of her parents,
who were both killed

00:22:36.690 --> 00:22:39.350
in the same plane crash, and
who'd left her the house.

00:22:39.350 --> 00:22:42.360
She told me of the job,
illustrating children's books,

00:22:42.360 --> 00:22:45.220
a job she'd backed into
accidentally, at the point

00:22:45.220 --> 00:22:46.900
she realized she would
never be a really

00:22:46.900 --> 00:22:48.800
competent medical Illustrator.

00:22:48.800 --> 00:22:50.620
And of how happy
she became whenever

00:22:50.620 --> 00:22:53.032
she was sent a new
book to illustrate.

00:22:53.032 --> 00:22:54.490
She told me she
taught life drawing

00:22:54.490 --> 00:22:58.420
to adults at the local community
college one evening a week.

00:22:58.420 --> 00:23:00.440
I saw no obvious
flaw in her life,

00:23:00.440 --> 00:23:03.565
no hole she could fill
by wishing, save one.

00:23:03.565 --> 00:23:05.440
"Your life is good,"
I told her. "But you

00:23:05.440 --> 00:23:07.130
have no one to share it with.

00:23:07.130 --> 00:23:09.370
Wish, and I will bring
you the perfect man.

00:23:09.370 --> 00:23:10.900
Or woman.

00:23:10.900 --> 00:23:12.010
A film star.

00:23:12.010 --> 00:23:16.310
A rich-- person--" "No need.

00:23:16.310 --> 00:23:18.660
I'm good," she said.

00:23:18.660 --> 00:23:20.690
We walked back to her
house, past houses

00:23:20.690 --> 00:23:22.140
dressed for Halloween.

00:23:22.140 --> 00:23:26.190
"This is not right," I told her.
"People always want things."

00:23:26.190 --> 00:23:26.960
"Not me.

00:23:26.960 --> 00:23:31.510
I've got everything I
need." "Then what do I do?"

00:23:31.510 --> 00:23:33.090
She thought for a moment.

00:23:33.090 --> 00:23:35.520
Then she pointed
at her front yard.

00:23:35.520 --> 00:23:38.400
"Can you rake the leaves?"

00:23:38.400 --> 00:23:41.859
"Is that your wish?" "No.

00:23:41.859 --> 00:23:43.400
Just something you
could do while I'm

00:23:43.400 --> 00:23:46.520
getting our dinner ready."

00:23:46.520 --> 00:23:49.020
I raked the leaves into
a heap by the hedge,

00:23:49.020 --> 00:23:51.100
to stop the wind from
blowing it apart.

00:23:51.100 --> 00:23:53.090
After dinner, I
washed up the dishes.

00:23:53.090 --> 00:23:55.780
I spent the night in
Hazel's spare bedroom.

00:23:55.780 --> 00:23:57.630
It wasn't that she
didn't want help.

00:23:57.630 --> 00:23:58.940
She let me help.

00:23:58.940 --> 00:24:02.227
I ran errands for her, picked
up art supplies and groceries.

00:24:02.227 --> 00:24:04.060
On days she'd been
painting for a long time,

00:24:04.060 --> 00:24:06.230
she let me rub her
neck and shoulders.

00:24:06.230 --> 00:24:08.900
I have good, firm hands.

00:24:08.900 --> 00:24:12.170
Shortly before Thanksgiving, I
moved out of the spare bedroom,

00:24:12.170 --> 00:24:17.210
across the hall, into the
main bedroom, and Hazel's bed.

00:24:17.210 --> 00:24:19.780
I watched her face this
morning as she slept.

00:24:19.780 --> 00:24:23.300
I stared at the shapes her
lips make when she sleeps.

00:24:23.300 --> 00:24:25.050
The creeping sunlight
touched her face,

00:24:25.050 --> 00:24:29.070
and she opened her eyes and
stared at me, and she smiled.

00:24:29.070 --> 00:24:33.660
"You know what I never asked,
she said, "is what about you?"

00:24:33.660 --> 00:24:35.700
"What would you
wish for if I asked

00:24:35.700 --> 00:24:38.430
what your three wishes were?"

00:24:38.430 --> 00:24:40.090
I thought for moment.

00:24:40.090 --> 00:24:42.730
I put my arm around her,
and she snuggled her head

00:24:42.730 --> 00:24:44.990
into my shoulder.

00:24:44.990 --> 00:24:47.350
"It's OK," I told her.

00:24:47.350 --> 00:25:02.280
"I'm good."

00:25:02.280 --> 00:25:07.100
AMANDA PALMER: So, one last
tune for you guys, and then

00:25:07.100 --> 00:25:09.920
and then we'll do questions
and talking and stuff.

00:25:13.360 --> 00:25:16.080
And this is also-- all the
stuff we've done here today

00:25:16.080 --> 00:25:17.210
is actually on the record.

00:25:17.210 --> 00:25:17.940
Isn't it?

00:25:17.940 --> 00:25:20.920
Or no, except for the
Calendar of Tales.

00:25:20.920 --> 00:25:23.770
Yeah, but everything else is.

00:25:23.770 --> 00:25:28.650
And so, as you can see, I play
the piano and the ukulele--

00:25:28.650 --> 00:25:32.260
the ukulele not really
as good as the piano.

00:25:32.260 --> 00:25:37.087
I'm a real fan recently of--
well, it's not a new idea,

00:25:37.087 --> 00:25:39.420
but I think it's great to
play an instrument that you're

00:25:39.420 --> 00:25:40.690
shitty at.

00:25:40.690 --> 00:25:43.377
It's very liberating.

00:25:43.377 --> 00:25:44.793
This is sort of a
song about that,

00:25:44.793 --> 00:25:46.844
and it's called "The
Ukulele Anthem."

00:25:46.844 --> 00:25:48.719
[MUSIC - AMANDA PALMER,
"THE UKULELE ANTHEM"]

00:31:24.999 --> 00:31:26.040
AMANDA PALMER: Thank you.

00:31:34.775 --> 00:31:37.150
ALAN LIGHT: So let's talk a
little bit about these shows,

00:31:37.150 --> 00:31:38.650
these shows you're
playing and these

00:31:38.650 --> 00:31:44.240
shows that you've recorded onto
this "Evening With" record.

00:31:44.240 --> 00:31:48.410
Is it more interesting for
you guys to combine your work

00:31:48.410 --> 00:31:51.320
or to combine your audiences?

00:31:51.320 --> 00:31:52.770
NEIL GAIMAN:
Actually, the reason

00:31:52.770 --> 00:31:56.330
why we did them was
a little bit of both.

00:31:56.330 --> 00:31:57.750
We never get free time.

00:31:57.750 --> 00:32:01.770
We're both strangely
busy people.

00:32:01.770 --> 00:32:09.380
But, in 2011, we suddenly
found ourselves with 11 days

00:32:09.380 --> 00:32:13.810
where we had to start
out in LA, and we

00:32:13.810 --> 00:32:17.600
had to finish in Seattle, and
we didn't have anything to do.

00:32:17.600 --> 00:32:19.040
And it was amazing.

00:32:19.040 --> 00:32:25.730
And so, immediately we decided
to fill it by hiring a car

00:32:25.730 --> 00:32:27.710
and just driving
up the west coast.

00:32:27.710 --> 00:32:29.649
And we thought, well
we'll have a vacation.

00:32:29.649 --> 00:32:32.190
And then we thought, well, if
we're going to have a vacation,

00:32:32.190 --> 00:32:34.390
we'll get on each other's
nerves by day two,

00:32:34.390 --> 00:32:36.220
so we need something to do.

00:32:36.220 --> 00:32:38.810
And so that was the idea of
taking little theaters as we

00:32:38.810 --> 00:32:44.370
went and just doing
"An Evening With."

00:32:44.370 --> 00:32:48.930
And that, of course,
embiggened ridiculously very,

00:32:48.930 --> 00:32:49.880
very quickly.

00:32:49.880 --> 00:32:55.770
But what became fun was
the mingling the audiences.

00:32:55.770 --> 00:32:56.937
It was like a wedding.

00:32:56.937 --> 00:32:59.270
It was like that sort of --
"are you on the bride's side

00:32:59.270 --> 00:33:02.240
or the groom's side" thing.

00:33:02.240 --> 00:33:05.790
And we'd meet people
afterwards at the signings,

00:33:05.790 --> 00:33:07.600
and we'd hang around
and say hello.

00:33:07.600 --> 00:33:09.810
And there would be people
who would just ignore me

00:33:09.810 --> 00:33:13.892
completely, head over to Amanda
with their Dresden Dolls CDs.

00:33:13.892 --> 00:33:16.100
Then there'd be people who'd
ignore her and come over

00:33:16.100 --> 00:33:17.180
to me with their Sandmans.

00:33:17.180 --> 00:33:19.555
And then there'd be the people
who'd just come up and go,

00:33:19.555 --> 00:33:22.320
can't believe you two--
my favorite writer.

00:33:22.320 --> 00:33:24.040
Like, aw, this is just the best.

00:33:28.270 --> 00:33:30.780
ALAN LIGHT: Given
that you've both

00:33:30.780 --> 00:33:33.619
constructed these lives
that sort of enable

00:33:33.619 --> 00:33:35.160
you to do whatever
you want, whenever

00:33:35.160 --> 00:33:39.850
you want-- it's the remarkable
thing about it-- what is it

00:33:39.850 --> 00:33:43.220
that these shows have
enabled you to do,

00:33:43.220 --> 00:33:48.125
have brought out that's
different than any other forum?

00:33:48.125 --> 00:33:50.806
AMANDA PALMER: That's
a good question.

00:33:50.806 --> 00:33:52.180
It's fresh in my
mind right now--

00:33:52.180 --> 00:33:55.220
we did a Reddit-- was
that two days ago?

00:33:55.220 --> 00:33:56.860
Yeah, two days ago, thanks.

00:33:56.860 --> 00:33:58.110
We did a Reddit two days ago--

00:33:58.110 --> 00:34:02.180
NEIL GAIMAN: Several years ago
in out of internet time, but--

00:34:02.180 --> 00:34:03.950
AMANDA PALMER: And
someone asked--

00:34:03.950 --> 00:34:07.500
I've been talking a lot
publicly, nowadays, and writing

00:34:07.500 --> 00:34:10.810
a lot, about internet nastiness.

00:34:10.810 --> 00:34:13.360
And it's actually a
hot topic in general.

00:34:13.360 --> 00:34:15.366
Not because I think
there's necessarily,

00:34:15.366 --> 00:34:17.199
particularly any more
of it today than there

00:34:17.199 --> 00:34:18.429
was last week or last year.

00:34:18.429 --> 00:34:23.159
But it's so
pervasive that people

00:34:23.159 --> 00:34:25.615
seem to be trying to figure
out, OK, well, clearly it's

00:34:25.615 --> 00:34:26.239
not going away.

00:34:26.239 --> 00:34:27.572
How the fuck do we deal with it?

00:34:27.572 --> 00:34:31.889
Especially as artists,
and as women or whatever.

00:34:31.889 --> 00:34:35.480
And we talked on
Reddit about how

00:34:35.480 --> 00:34:39.030
Neil and I had our own
particular relationship

00:34:39.030 --> 00:34:41.300
with our fans and
with our haters

00:34:41.300 --> 00:34:42.760
before we met each other.

00:34:42.760 --> 00:34:47.328
And then, we sort of inherited
new forms of hate when--

00:34:47.328 --> 00:34:49.453
ALAN LIGHT: They're still
making new forms of hate.

00:34:52.440 --> 00:34:55.639
AMANDA PALMER: I think,
maybe, subconsciously, it

00:34:55.639 --> 00:35:00.296
was also a way of going
out in public and saying,

00:35:00.296 --> 00:35:02.985
we're two people who are
going to do things together.

00:35:02.985 --> 00:35:05.364
And, in a way, kind of like
the wedding, it was like,

00:35:05.364 --> 00:35:07.280
you guys are going to
have to meet my husband.

00:35:07.280 --> 00:35:09.900
He's a really, really nice guy.

00:35:09.900 --> 00:35:10.900
And vice versa.

00:35:10.900 --> 00:35:13.560
And I wanted them to see him.

00:35:13.560 --> 00:35:15.305
I wanted them to know him.

00:35:15.305 --> 00:35:16.930
NEIL GAIMAN: It was
really interesting,

00:35:16.930 --> 00:35:23.740
I think, for us also because
we have both been getting up

00:35:23.740 --> 00:35:26.170
on stage is in front
of audiences doing

00:35:26.170 --> 00:35:28.680
the thing that we do for
years and years and years.

00:35:28.680 --> 00:35:32.510
And if there's one thing that we
are both completely certain of,

00:35:32.510 --> 00:35:38.120
it is that the buck stops
with us, with each individual.

00:35:38.120 --> 00:35:40.420
You know, if it's my
reading or whatever,

00:35:40.420 --> 00:35:43.140
anyone else can
have input, but I'm

00:35:43.140 --> 00:35:46.050
the one that gets to decide
what I read, what happens.

00:35:46.050 --> 00:35:49.780
And Amanda, gigging, it
all ends up with her.

00:35:49.780 --> 00:35:51.530
And so, you suddenly
had these two people

00:35:51.530 --> 00:35:58.810
who are completely used to being
the last authority-- questions

00:35:58.810 --> 00:36:00.380
could be raised,
ideas could be had,

00:36:00.380 --> 00:36:04.055
but, finally, it would
get to me or get to Amanda

00:36:04.055 --> 00:36:06.180
and we'd say, well, actually
we'll do it like this.

00:36:06.180 --> 00:36:08.110
And suddenly, we'd
get to the point

00:36:08.110 --> 00:36:10.651
where Amanda would say, well,
we're going to do it like this.

00:36:10.651 --> 00:36:13.040
And I'd say, no, we're not.

00:36:13.040 --> 00:36:13.930
Or vice versa.

00:36:13.930 --> 00:36:14.430
And--

00:36:14.430 --> 00:36:16.910
AMANDA PALMER: Oh my god,
it's like being married.

00:36:16.910 --> 00:36:17.900
NEIL GAIMAN: It was.

00:36:17.900 --> 00:36:20.310
It was the most,
sort of, married,

00:36:20.310 --> 00:36:21.870
bumping into each
other, and I think

00:36:21.870 --> 00:36:26.520
it taught both of us
humility, especially me.

00:36:26.520 --> 00:36:27.770
AMANDA PALMER: Oh, both of us.

00:36:27.770 --> 00:36:31.230
NEIL GAIMAN: And
actually taught us

00:36:31.230 --> 00:36:34.470
to cooperate in ways that,
I think-- it was nice,

00:36:34.470 --> 00:36:38.410
it was like a pressure
cooker, because it was the one

00:36:38.410 --> 00:36:41.200
area of our lives in which
we both reigned supreme,

00:36:41.200 --> 00:36:43.330
and suddenly we had
to give that up.

00:36:43.330 --> 00:36:46.100
AMANDA PALMER: Yeah, and also
I had a chip on my shoulder,

00:36:46.100 --> 00:36:48.650
maybe, about, well,
I'm the stage person.

00:36:48.650 --> 00:36:51.394
So I even thought
that, maybe, when

00:36:51.394 --> 00:36:53.310
we would get into these
arguments about, like,

00:36:53.310 --> 00:36:55.630
the chair should go here or
the chair should go there--

00:36:55.630 --> 00:36:56.740
NEIL GAIMAN: We had
those arguments.

00:36:56.740 --> 00:36:58.698
AMANDA PALMER: And we
did have those arguments.

00:37:00.580 --> 00:37:03.270
That's one of the weird
things about being married

00:37:03.270 --> 00:37:07.580
to an artist, or a person who is
used to doing big public events

00:37:07.580 --> 00:37:09.655
or whatever, is that I
felt like the expert,

00:37:09.655 --> 00:37:11.780
and Neil felt like the
expert, and we would sort of

00:37:11.780 --> 00:37:13.196
be there going
like, but, but but,

00:37:13.196 --> 00:37:17.940
but but-- You could look at
so many parts of the tour

00:37:17.940 --> 00:37:20.030
and the recording
and the decisions

00:37:20.030 --> 00:37:23.710
as a total marriage
metaphor, because a lot of it

00:37:23.710 --> 00:37:26.080
was actually-- not the
arguments we would get into,

00:37:26.080 --> 00:37:29.170
but just how we would actually
smooth things out and not

00:37:29.170 --> 00:37:31.560
actually get angry at each
other and kind of learn

00:37:31.560 --> 00:37:32.704
how to do the dance.

00:37:32.704 --> 00:37:34.620
NEIL GAIMAN: Even doing
the Kickstarter video.

00:37:34.620 --> 00:37:37.078
When we decided we were actually
going to do this properly,

00:37:37.078 --> 00:37:40.492
we suddenly went, we
might as well record it.

00:37:40.492 --> 00:37:41.950
And if we're going
to record it, we

00:37:41.950 --> 00:37:45.642
may as well record it properly,
and why not go to Kickstarter?

00:37:45.642 --> 00:37:47.850
This was in the relatively
early days of Kickstarter.

00:37:47.850 --> 00:37:54.799
So we tried recording a serious
video in which we explained

00:37:54.799 --> 00:37:56.340
what we were doing,
and why we needed

00:37:56.340 --> 00:37:57.710
the money, and stuff like that.

00:37:57.710 --> 00:37:59.120
And we did that about
three or four times,

00:37:59.120 --> 00:38:00.870
and all we knew is
that, by the end of it,

00:38:00.870 --> 00:38:03.500
we hated it and each other.

00:38:03.500 --> 00:38:05.810
AMANDA PALMER: And Neil
had a terrible cold.

00:38:05.810 --> 00:38:08.680
NEIL GAIMAN: But then,
time was running out,

00:38:08.680 --> 00:38:10.530
and then we had to
do one suddenly.

00:38:10.530 --> 00:38:13.220
We'd realized it was our
only chance together,

00:38:13.220 --> 00:38:18.590
and I'd lost my voice, and
had this horrible cold,

00:38:18.590 --> 00:38:19.950
and was sick.

00:38:19.950 --> 00:38:22.780
And we were in Brighton, where
Amanda was about to do a gig,

00:38:22.780 --> 00:38:26.120
so I grabbed a banana
from the dressing room,

00:38:26.120 --> 00:38:28.172
we walked down onto
the beach, and Amanda

00:38:28.172 --> 00:38:29.630
explained to the
world what we were

00:38:29.630 --> 00:38:31.838
going to do in this Kickstarter
while I ate a banana.

00:38:31.838 --> 00:38:33.142
AMANDA PALMER: It was perfect.

00:38:33.142 --> 00:38:33.820
NEIL GAIMAN: And I think--

00:38:33.820 --> 00:38:35.944
AMANDA PALMER: It was a
performance art Kickstarter

00:38:35.944 --> 00:38:36.600
video.

00:38:36.600 --> 00:38:40.450
NEIL GAIMAN: As Kickstarter
videos, it was the best.

00:38:40.450 --> 00:38:42.676
AMANDA PALMER:
And also very much

00:38:42.676 --> 00:38:44.800
in keeping with our stage
personas, which is-- he's

00:38:44.800 --> 00:38:47.860
really good at being
the straight guy,

00:38:47.860 --> 00:38:49.720
and I'm the obnoxious,
ridiculous one.

00:38:49.720 --> 00:38:51.830
And we sort of
balance each other.

00:38:51.830 --> 00:38:54.288
NEIL GAIMAN: I like to think
of it as English and American.

00:38:55.730 --> 00:38:57.028
AMANDA PALMER: Ow.

00:38:57.028 --> 00:38:57.528
Ow!

00:39:01.464 --> 00:39:02.380
ALAN LIGHT: All right.

00:39:02.380 --> 00:39:07.370
Well, coming off the
ropes from that one--

00:39:07.370 --> 00:39:10.090
I inevitably will want to come
back to the Kickstarter stuff,

00:39:10.090 --> 00:39:12.670
but I want to ask
you a little bit

00:39:12.670 --> 00:39:18.470
about these modes of creativity.

00:39:18.470 --> 00:39:22.120
And, I guess, Neil, even
within recent months

00:39:22.120 --> 00:39:25.420
there's been the
novel, the comic book,

00:39:25.420 --> 00:39:31.460
the Twitter stories-- all of
these different mechanisms

00:39:31.460 --> 00:39:34.530
or constructions that you
use to get these stories out

00:39:34.530 --> 00:39:35.570
in the world.

00:39:35.570 --> 00:39:37.580
How do you determine,
and when do you

00:39:37.580 --> 00:39:43.120
determine, what goes
where, what idea is then

00:39:43.120 --> 00:39:46.490
going to manifest in which way?

00:39:46.490 --> 00:39:50.170
NEIL GAIMAN: A
lot of the times I

00:39:50.170 --> 00:39:54.050
have a vague idea going into it.

00:39:54.050 --> 00:39:58.830
The medium actually defines what
goes into it a lot of the time.

00:39:58.830 --> 00:40:00.280
A lot of the time I'm wrong.

00:40:00.280 --> 00:40:04.590
I had two actual books come
out this year-- "The Ocean

00:40:04.590 --> 00:40:08.570
at the End of the Lane" and
"Fortunately, the Milk,"

00:40:08.570 --> 00:40:11.240
my children's book.

00:40:11.240 --> 00:40:14.960
And both of them started
off as something else.

00:40:14.960 --> 00:40:17.750
"Ocean at the End of the
Lane" was a short story

00:40:17.750 --> 00:40:20.670
that I was writing to send
Amanda when she was recording

00:40:20.670 --> 00:40:23.205
"Theater Is Evil," because
I missed her, and I thought,

00:40:23.205 --> 00:40:24.750
I'll send her a short story.

00:40:24.750 --> 00:40:26.490
It'll show her I love her.

00:40:26.490 --> 00:40:29.480
She'll be impressed.

00:40:29.480 --> 00:40:31.420
Better than flowers.

00:40:31.420 --> 00:40:33.420
Except that it just kept
going, and by the time

00:40:33.420 --> 00:40:36.610
I finished it, she'd
returned from Australia,

00:40:36.610 --> 00:40:39.510
was mixing the album in
Dallas, and I did a word count

00:40:39.510 --> 00:40:43.614
and discovered I'd written
a novel, accidentally.

00:40:43.614 --> 00:40:45.530
"Fortunately, the Milk"
started out in my head

00:40:45.530 --> 00:40:47.090
as a picture book.

00:40:47.090 --> 00:40:49.110
And I just started writing it.

00:40:49.110 --> 00:40:51.630
And I was writing
it in a notebook.

00:40:51.630 --> 00:40:56.620
And whenever I felt like
I needed cheering up I'd

00:40:56.620 --> 00:40:58.920
go to the notebook and I'd
write about 1,000 words

00:40:58.920 --> 00:41:00.420
of "Fortunately,
the Milk," it would

00:41:00.420 --> 00:41:04.670
make me smile, and then I'd put
it away and forget about it.

00:41:04.670 --> 00:41:06.060
And when I got to
the end, again,

00:41:06.060 --> 00:41:07.579
I typed it up,
looked at it, went--

00:41:07.579 --> 00:41:10.120
this is much, much, much, too
long to ever be a picture book.

00:41:10.120 --> 00:41:11.840
It's actually a book.

00:41:11.840 --> 00:41:17.010
So in those cases
I was just wrong.

00:41:17.010 --> 00:41:19.260
Sometimes there are things
where you sort of go, well,

00:41:19.260 --> 00:41:22.910
look, if it's in your head
and it's got pictures in,

00:41:22.910 --> 00:41:25.580
it's probably not a novel.

00:41:25.580 --> 00:41:28.360
If the pictures
actually move and make

00:41:28.360 --> 00:41:30.390
sounds, then maybe it's
television or a movie.

00:41:32.960 --> 00:41:34.860
If you can keep
them kind of static,

00:41:34.860 --> 00:41:38.340
then maybe it's
going to be a comic.

00:41:38.340 --> 00:41:41.050
And sometimes I'll try something
in several different ways.

00:41:41.050 --> 00:41:43.440
I'll have an idea
that I know works,

00:41:43.440 --> 00:41:46.385
and I'll try it as a poem
and watch it fail as a poem

00:41:46.385 --> 00:41:48.010
and go, OK, well, if
you're not a poem,

00:41:48.010 --> 00:41:49.919
then maybe you're a
short story-- maybe

00:41:49.919 --> 00:41:50.960
you're a comic, whatever.

00:41:50.960 --> 00:41:53.190
I'll come back
and sometimes play

00:41:53.190 --> 00:41:55.000
with things in two or
three different times

00:41:55.000 --> 00:41:56.499
until I feel like
I've got it right.

00:41:59.224 --> 00:42:01.140
ALAN LIGHT: I don't know
if this is the Amanda

00:42:01.140 --> 00:42:04.870
version of that question,
but it seems related.

00:42:04.870 --> 00:42:09.220
You've told the story
onstage and offstage

00:42:09.220 --> 00:42:18.070
about writing "The Bed Song" and
the process and transformation

00:42:18.070 --> 00:42:21.790
that came at the end of
making that song happen.

00:42:21.790 --> 00:42:25.220
Can you tell that story and
talk about that a little bit,

00:42:25.220 --> 00:42:28.050
which seems to me
also about, where

00:42:28.050 --> 00:42:30.347
does the creativity take you?

00:42:30.347 --> 00:42:31.180
AMANDA PALMER: Yeah.

00:42:31.180 --> 00:42:32.940
"The Bed Song" is
interesting for me.

00:42:32.940 --> 00:42:34.356
I wish I'd played
it for you guys,

00:42:34.356 --> 00:42:37.570
because you'd have
some context, but it's

00:42:37.570 --> 00:42:39.600
a solo piano song
on the new record.

00:42:39.600 --> 00:42:44.170
And it's pretty simple
to explain, actually.

00:42:44.170 --> 00:42:49.560
It's almost like a fictional
narrative of a couple

00:42:49.560 --> 00:42:51.260
told in the first
person, basically,

00:42:51.260 --> 00:42:53.930
starting at the beginning
of the relationship.

00:42:53.930 --> 00:42:55.970
And it chronicles,
with each verse,

00:42:55.970 --> 00:42:58.865
the way the beds change
in the relationship.

00:42:58.865 --> 00:43:03.099
And it starts out, and
it's this crazy couple

00:43:03.099 --> 00:43:05.390
at a party sleeping in a
sleeping bag at their friends'

00:43:05.390 --> 00:43:08.160
house, and through the
shitty futon at college,

00:43:08.160 --> 00:43:12.510
and through getting
married and getting

00:43:12.510 --> 00:43:14.552
a proper bed in a condo.

00:43:14.552 --> 00:43:16.760
And while this is all
happening, the relationship's--

00:43:19.821 --> 00:43:20.570
NEIL GAIMAN:Dying.

00:43:20.570 --> 00:43:21.445
AMANDA PALMER: Dying.

00:43:21.445 --> 00:43:22.420
Encoldening.

00:43:22.420 --> 00:43:25.420
I don't know,
becoming more distant.

00:43:25.420 --> 00:43:28.620
And the bed just becomes
this metaphor of space.

00:43:28.620 --> 00:43:31.370
And I don't usually
write songs like that.

00:43:33.890 --> 00:43:36.460
But I'm so impressed
by Neil because he's

00:43:36.460 --> 00:43:39.130
such a great fiction thinker.

00:43:39.130 --> 00:43:42.910
And usually when I think
about ideas and songs,

00:43:42.910 --> 00:43:46.270
it's always so personal.

00:43:46.270 --> 00:43:49.670
And even my sort of
fictional work in the past

00:43:49.670 --> 00:43:54.040
has always been like some
very, very close reflection

00:43:54.040 --> 00:43:54.830
of myself.

00:43:54.830 --> 00:43:57.714
But very close, so close
that you look at it,

00:43:57.714 --> 00:44:00.380
and you see the ingredients, and
you see that it's not quite me,

00:44:00.380 --> 00:44:01.580
but it might as well be.

00:44:01.580 --> 00:44:04.121
NEIL GAIMAN: Close enough that
your mother can get irritated.

00:44:04.121 --> 00:44:05.456
AMANDA PALMER: Exactly.

00:44:05.456 --> 00:44:08.909
But "The Bed Song," actually,
I haven't experienced all of

00:44:08.909 --> 00:44:09.450
those stages.

00:44:09.450 --> 00:44:11.200
I've definitely been
in relationships

00:44:11.200 --> 00:44:15.690
where distance
happened, but this

00:44:15.690 --> 00:44:21.274
was like writing an epic poem of
all painful relationships ever.

00:44:21.274 --> 00:44:23.940
And I was really proud of having
written it, because I was like,

00:44:23.940 --> 00:44:25.990
actually I'm proud
that it's a good song,

00:44:25.990 --> 00:44:28.190
but I'm actually
proud that I managed

00:44:28.190 --> 00:44:31.180
to write a good work of fiction.

00:44:31.180 --> 00:44:33.460
ALAN LIGHT: Which you
also sort of webcast,

00:44:33.460 --> 00:44:36.680
Twitter-cast, the
writing of, right?

00:44:36.680 --> 00:44:38.712
AMANDA PALMER:
Yeah, and so that's

00:44:38.712 --> 00:44:39.920
another thing about the song.

00:44:39.920 --> 00:44:44.780
So, another thing that happened
while writing the song.

00:44:44.780 --> 00:44:49.340
And I got the idea for the song
probably a week or so before I

00:44:49.340 --> 00:44:49.840
wrote it.

00:44:49.840 --> 00:44:52.630
The idea popped in and the idea
of using the bed as a metaphor.

00:44:52.630 --> 00:44:54.421
And I thought, aw,
that'll be a great song.

00:44:54.421 --> 00:44:56.600
If I get that right,
that'll be a great song.

00:44:56.600 --> 00:44:59.720
And I sat myself down at the
piano one day to write it.

00:44:59.720 --> 00:45:04.590
And up until that point,
I had had a real hangup

00:45:04.590 --> 00:45:10.250
about what it meant to be a
good, disciplined creator.

00:45:10.250 --> 00:45:12.784
Which is, at the moment of
creation, and at the moment

00:45:12.784 --> 00:45:14.950
where I'm really going to
sit down and write a song,

00:45:14.950 --> 00:45:18.700
I need to turn my phone off, not
be distracted, shut my computer

00:45:18.700 --> 00:45:20.950
down, put all the
shit away, and write,

00:45:20.950 --> 00:45:22.490
which is what real writers do.

00:45:27.500 --> 00:45:29.170
And I have a huge
Twitter following

00:45:29.170 --> 00:45:31.350
that I have a constant,
ongoing communication

00:45:31.350 --> 00:45:32.640
relationship with.

00:45:32.640 --> 00:45:35.520
And just this time,
I decided, you know,

00:45:35.520 --> 00:45:39.236
fuck it, I'm going to actually,
instead of closing down,

00:45:39.236 --> 00:45:40.110
I'm going to open up.

00:45:40.110 --> 00:45:41.590
And I'm going to announce
to my Twitter feed

00:45:41.590 --> 00:45:42.640
that I'm writing a song.

00:45:42.640 --> 00:45:44.666
And actually, by
doing that, I feel

00:45:44.666 --> 00:45:46.040
like I'm going to
have to be more

00:45:46.040 --> 00:45:48.373
disciplined because they're
all going to kind of keep me

00:45:48.373 --> 00:45:50.190
on task.

00:45:50.190 --> 00:45:51.500
And they did.

00:45:51.500 --> 00:45:55.100
And it's not like I set
up a webcasting station

00:45:55.100 --> 00:45:56.040
at the piano.

00:45:56.040 --> 00:45:58.200
They didn't watch my process.

00:45:58.200 --> 00:45:59.990
But they knew, and
they were there.

00:45:59.990 --> 00:46:02.092
And every 20 minutes
or so-- probably

00:46:02.092 --> 00:46:04.550
took me three hours to write
the song, and every 20 minutes

00:46:04.550 --> 00:46:07.720
or so I'd take a picture
of all my scratched

00:46:07.720 --> 00:46:12.290
out words and the piano and
my fan base is great that way.

00:46:12.290 --> 00:46:14.590
They were like a
bunch of cheerleaders

00:46:14.590 --> 00:46:16.547
who were just sitting
there on Twitter saying,

00:46:16.547 --> 00:46:17.380
this sounds amazing.

00:46:17.380 --> 00:46:18.980
We're so glad you're writing.

00:46:18.980 --> 00:46:20.890
We can't wait to hear the song.

00:46:20.890 --> 00:46:23.800
And I realized I could do both.

00:46:23.800 --> 00:46:26.830
And I could tap into the
enthusiasm of the internet

00:46:26.830 --> 00:46:30.560
without letting it destroy
my creative process,

00:46:30.560 --> 00:46:34.669
and that was a huge revelation.

00:46:34.669 --> 00:46:37.210
And the song wound up being one
of the best I'd ever written,

00:46:37.210 --> 00:46:43.080
I thought, and so I didn't
take that lesson lightly.

00:46:43.080 --> 00:46:45.562
ALAN LIGHT: So one
more for each and then

00:46:45.562 --> 00:46:47.020
we'll go to questions
for you guys,

00:46:47.020 --> 00:46:50.830
so start organizing
your thoughts.

00:46:50.830 --> 00:46:57.160
Inevitably, I must ask about the
famous, infamous, celebrated,

00:46:57.160 --> 00:47:01.360
Earth-shattering
Kickstarter campaign,

00:47:01.360 --> 00:47:05.660
and all of the attention
that it received,

00:47:05.660 --> 00:47:08.640
more so than anything else.

00:47:08.640 --> 00:47:12.760
That there was so much
talk and so many responses,

00:47:12.760 --> 00:47:16.020
from-- we have seen the
future of the industry,

00:47:16.020 --> 00:47:22.120
to she's a total hustler, to
every response you could have.

00:47:22.120 --> 00:47:25.110
From this vantage
point now, what

00:47:25.110 --> 00:47:31.028
do you take as the biggest
lessons from the $1 million

00:47:31.028 --> 00:47:31.986
Kickstarter experience?

00:47:34.800 --> 00:47:36.550
NEIL GAIMAN: Don't
give them free postage.

00:47:36.550 --> 00:47:40.070
AMANDA PALMER:Yeah, don't
do free internet postage,

00:47:40.070 --> 00:47:40.900
that's the big one.

00:47:43.660 --> 00:47:46.590
I learned so many things
in so many departments,

00:47:46.590 --> 00:47:50.770
and I could talk about it
for half an hour, so I won't.

00:47:50.770 --> 00:47:53.330
And actually, my brain is
sort of prepped on this.

00:47:53.330 --> 00:47:57.390
I was in Vienna last week
and doing a panel like this

00:47:57.390 --> 00:48:01.670
on crowd funding and we got into
really dark, interesting talks

00:48:01.670 --> 00:48:04.320
about social capital.

00:48:04.320 --> 00:48:08.180
And a lot of the
conversation, lately,

00:48:08.180 --> 00:48:10.212
that I've been involved
in and wondering about,

00:48:10.212 --> 00:48:11.670
and what everyone's
wondering about

00:48:11.670 --> 00:48:14.730
is-- what if you're not like me?

00:48:14.730 --> 00:48:19.600
And I can say it's the future
of music, but it's my future.

00:48:19.600 --> 00:48:22.125
I'm good at this, and I'm
good at communicating,

00:48:22.125 --> 00:48:24.110
and I like hanging
out with my fans,

00:48:24.110 --> 00:48:26.110
and I love tweeting all
day and I love blogging,

00:48:26.110 --> 00:48:28.284
and I love using platforms
like Kickstarter.

00:48:28.284 --> 00:48:29.700
That doesn't
necessarily mean it's

00:48:29.700 --> 00:48:33.430
for everyone or
for every project.

00:48:33.430 --> 00:48:43.440
And I think one of the
biggest-- not mistakes,

00:48:43.440 --> 00:48:46.270
but sort of misguided things,
maybe, about the Kickstarter,

00:48:46.270 --> 00:48:52.570
was that I drank the
Kool-Aid that my Kickstarter

00:48:52.570 --> 00:48:57.850
success would translate
into commercial success.

00:48:57.850 --> 00:49:05.090
And so I found myself
thinking that, in a weird way,

00:49:05.090 --> 00:49:09.010
I wish I had just taken my fan
base for granted and done it

00:49:09.010 --> 00:49:12.570
with them, instead of thinking
that I could use them as a step

00:49:12.570 --> 00:49:17.676
to get to whatever that
next magical place was.

00:49:17.676 --> 00:49:19.050
I had already
learned that lesson

00:49:19.050 --> 00:49:21.171
six times over with
the record label,

00:49:21.171 --> 00:49:23.670
and I thought it was going to
be different with Kickstarter,

00:49:23.670 --> 00:49:27.000
that every time I would walk
into the office at Roadrunner

00:49:27.000 --> 00:49:31.200
Records-- not very far from
here, and now nonexistent.

00:49:31.200 --> 00:49:33.200
But they would say, this
is going to be the one,

00:49:33.200 --> 00:49:34.085
this is the moment.

00:49:34.085 --> 00:49:36.710
This is going to be the project
that is going to actually bring

00:49:36.710 --> 00:49:39.480
you to the next place, which
is the place you want to be.

00:49:39.480 --> 00:49:42.200
And I would go, oh, wow, great,
and an office of 30 people

00:49:42.200 --> 00:49:45.400
seem to believe it, and seem
to believe that we should

00:49:45.400 --> 00:49:49.070
be putting our energy not
into where we feel safe

00:49:49.070 --> 00:49:52.240
and into those we love but
into foreign structures

00:49:52.240 --> 00:49:55.100
so that we can go out
and conquer and be

00:49:55.100 --> 00:49:56.520
an imperial band.

00:49:56.520 --> 00:49:59.490
And actually, if I've
learned any lesson

00:49:59.490 --> 00:50:03.200
it's that even those
closely around me,

00:50:03.200 --> 00:50:06.640
very well-intentioned,
shouldn't be telling me

00:50:06.640 --> 00:50:08.110
what my instincts are.

00:50:08.110 --> 00:50:11.160
And I am very gullible.

00:50:11.160 --> 00:50:15.130
So that was the biggest
one, because if I

00:50:15.130 --> 00:50:17.660
had just done the Kickstarter
and delivered the record,

00:50:17.660 --> 00:50:20.870
and not also paid
for giant videos

00:50:20.870 --> 00:50:23.200
and not paid for huge
marketing campaigns

00:50:23.200 --> 00:50:28.920
and not tried to reach
for the mainstream success

00:50:28.920 --> 00:50:32.100
that my team all just flat
assumed that the record would

00:50:32.100 --> 00:50:35.601
have, I think I would
have been happier.

00:50:35.601 --> 00:50:36.600
NEIL GAIMAN: And richer.

00:50:36.600 --> 00:50:37.125
AMANDA PALMER: And richer.

00:50:37.125 --> 00:50:39.572
Yeah, but richer-- I don't
really care about richer,

00:50:39.572 --> 00:50:40.530
but happier I do care--

00:50:40.530 --> 00:50:40.830
NEIL GAIMAN: I
know, but there was

00:50:40.830 --> 00:50:43.190
all of those people seem
to be assuming that you,

00:50:43.190 --> 00:50:45.850
having had the Kickstarter,
you were now Uncle Scrooge-ing.

00:50:45.850 --> 00:50:47.510
You had a swimming pool.

00:50:47.510 --> 00:50:48.865
It was filled with dollars.

00:50:48.865 --> 00:50:50.490
And you would take
off all your clothes

00:50:50.490 --> 00:50:53.500
and plunge into
it like a dolphin.

00:50:53.500 --> 00:50:55.430
AMANDA PALMER: That's a
wonderful image, Neil.

00:50:55.430 --> 00:50:56.970
ALAN LIGHT: Maybe a song.

00:50:56.970 --> 00:50:59.880
AMANDA PALMER: But yeah,
and if nothing else,

00:50:59.880 --> 00:51:05.420
it also lifted the
rug up on how amazed I

00:51:05.420 --> 00:51:07.970
was that really intelligent
people didn't understand

00:51:07.970 --> 00:51:10.060
how business worked.

00:51:10.060 --> 00:51:13.119
Like, it really amazed
me that smart journalists

00:51:13.119 --> 00:51:14.910
at smart magazines
would be like, well, now

00:51:14.910 --> 00:51:17.237
that you have $1.2
million in the bank, what

00:51:17.237 --> 00:51:18.070
are you going to do?

00:51:18.070 --> 00:51:20.528
And I'd be like, have you seen
the Kickstarter and the fact

00:51:20.528 --> 00:51:24.110
that I have to manufacture
$800,000 worth of shit

00:51:24.110 --> 00:51:27.500
and mail it to people--
and that it's a business?

00:51:27.500 --> 00:51:28.715
And that has brought--

00:51:28.715 --> 00:51:32.230
NEIL GAIMAN: I love the
guy on Reddit who asked,

00:51:32.230 --> 00:51:37.860
you say you spent over
$100,000 manufacturing CDs,

00:51:37.860 --> 00:51:42.660
yet you only asked for
$100,000 to start out with.

00:51:42.660 --> 00:51:45.580
How can you explain that?

00:51:45.580 --> 00:51:49.760
And I'm going, well if only
3,000 people had signed up,

00:51:49.760 --> 00:51:52.710
and she'd only
had $100,000, then

00:51:52.710 --> 00:51:54.750
she wouldn't have
had to manufacture--

00:51:54.750 --> 00:51:56.762
it was a sort of strange thing.

00:51:56.762 --> 00:51:58.470
AMANDA PALMER: Yeah,
and I fielded a lot.

00:51:58.470 --> 00:52:01.900
And so the bigger question--
and I'm about to write a book,

00:52:01.900 --> 00:52:03.650
and the book is
going to be centered

00:52:03.650 --> 00:52:06.700
around these weird
new questions that

00:52:06.700 --> 00:52:09.980
have come flooding into my life,
which is-- why do people think

00:52:09.980 --> 00:52:13.250
art is so much different
from running a business?

00:52:13.250 --> 00:52:19.250
And why is making a vinyl album,
in people's heads, so much

00:52:19.250 --> 00:52:21.070
different than making an iPhone?

00:52:21.070 --> 00:52:24.370
And why do artists get shit
for things that business people

00:52:24.370 --> 00:52:25.230
don't?

00:52:25.230 --> 00:52:26.680
And I can understand why.

00:52:26.680 --> 00:52:27.930
And artists are weird.

00:52:27.930 --> 00:52:31.640
And the way we feel
about commerce over here,

00:52:31.640 --> 00:52:35.500
and just like, I will make you
this thing and it costs $19.95.

00:52:35.500 --> 00:52:38.240
And the way people feel
about paintings or music

00:52:38.240 --> 00:52:39.290
is definitely different.

00:52:39.290 --> 00:52:42.560
But watching them
collide is fascinating.

00:52:42.560 --> 00:52:45.000
ALAN LIGHT: And is
where the action is.

00:52:45.000 --> 00:52:48.240
I mean that's where
we're living right now,

00:52:48.240 --> 00:52:50.210
is in those questions.

00:52:50.210 --> 00:52:52.800
Which brings me beautifully
to the final question

00:52:52.800 --> 00:52:57.390
I was going to ask Neil
and not hog the microphone.

00:52:57.390 --> 00:52:59.050
The other thing that
came out this year

00:52:59.050 --> 00:53:02.462
was the publication of
the "Make Great Art"--

00:53:02.462 --> 00:53:03.420
NEIL GAIMAN: My speech.

00:53:03.420 --> 00:53:05.640
ALAN LIGHT: Commencement
lecture, yes.

00:53:05.640 --> 00:53:06.570
So I'm curious.

00:53:06.570 --> 00:53:12.090
We have a roomful here,
maybe of artists, but maybe

00:53:12.090 --> 00:53:17.410
technology visionaries
and wizards and whatever

00:53:17.410 --> 00:53:20.920
it is that they do
within these walls.

00:53:20.920 --> 00:53:25.440
And I'm curious, without asking
you to deliver a speech that

00:53:25.440 --> 00:53:29.100
will go viral around the world
and cause people to quote

00:53:29.100 --> 00:53:36.790
from at numerous occasions--
would you modify,

00:53:36.790 --> 00:53:39.000
or how would you
modify the ideas

00:53:39.000 --> 00:53:42.470
that you spoke about in
that celebrated speech

00:53:42.470 --> 00:53:44.740
for a room that's like this one?

00:53:44.740 --> 00:53:47.940
NEIL GAIMAN: You
know, I wouldn't.

00:53:47.940 --> 00:53:51.650
What was fascinating for
me about that speech was,

00:53:51.650 --> 00:53:53.572
I gave a commencement
speech because I

00:53:53.572 --> 00:53:55.280
was asked to give a
commencement speech--

00:53:55.280 --> 00:53:56.976
I'd never given one before.

00:53:56.976 --> 00:53:58.886
And I'd write it and
I'd show it to Amanda,

00:53:58.886 --> 00:54:01.385
and she'd read it through and
she'd say, you can't say that.

00:54:01.385 --> 00:54:02.080
And I'd say why not?

00:54:02.080 --> 00:54:02.932
And she'd well that's
the kind of thing

00:54:02.932 --> 00:54:04.348
they say in
commencement speeches.

00:54:04.348 --> 00:54:06.760
And I wouldn't know.

00:54:06.760 --> 00:54:08.650
So what I did was
simply take everything

00:54:08.650 --> 00:54:11.550
I've learned in 30
years of being a writer

00:54:11.550 --> 00:54:16.100
and stick it into a speech,
like-- that was easy.

00:54:16.100 --> 00:54:18.180
And there is a bit
at the end where

00:54:18.180 --> 00:54:20.540
I started explaining
that what you

00:54:20.540 --> 00:54:24.260
do as an artist-- because it was
to the University of the Arts

00:54:24.260 --> 00:54:27.080
and a graduating
class of artists-- is,

00:54:27.080 --> 00:54:28.430
you make good art.

00:54:28.430 --> 00:54:32.710
And that actually
should be your response

00:54:32.710 --> 00:54:35.820
to all of the shit
you're going to run into.

00:54:35.820 --> 00:54:40.230
You know-- husband leaves
you, make good art.

00:54:40.230 --> 00:54:41.710
House burns down--
make good art.

00:54:44.347 --> 00:54:46.180
Something wonderful
happens-- make good art.

00:54:46.180 --> 00:54:47.880
That's what you do.

00:54:47.880 --> 00:54:51.130
And what I loved,
once it went out there

00:54:51.130 --> 00:54:54.550
and went viral, which is the
kind of unpredictable thing

00:54:54.550 --> 00:54:57.430
that sometimes happens,
and happens in this case.

00:54:57.430 --> 00:55:00.830
I'd see people on
Twitter, and on the web,

00:55:00.830 --> 00:55:04.550
and on comments saying,
well I'm an architect.

00:55:04.550 --> 00:55:07.430
Actually, it works if
you just cross out "art"

00:55:07.430 --> 00:55:09.140
and make "architecture."

00:55:09.140 --> 00:55:10.640
And someone else
is going, physics--

00:55:10.640 --> 00:55:13.460
you can make good physics.

00:55:13.460 --> 00:55:19.150
