01:06:41.905 --> 01:06:44.610
and you might not even
feel passionate about it.

01:06:44.610 --> 01:06:50.580
And so once you can do enough
work on yourself as a human,

01:06:50.580 --> 01:06:54.140
in the forgiveness department,
that you're not fitting

01:06:54.140 --> 01:06:56.240
the picture that
you had, the fraud

01:06:56.240 --> 01:07:01.169
police just-- You
still always fear

01:07:01.169 --> 01:07:02.460
that, I think, in a little way.

01:07:02.460 --> 01:07:04.793
But the more you work and the
more other people take you

01:07:04.793 --> 01:07:07.030
seriously, the easier it gets.

01:07:07.030 --> 01:07:09.150
NEIL GAIMAN: I was
actually in the audience

01:07:09.150 --> 01:07:11.245
at her commencement
speech, and I misheard her.

01:07:11.245 --> 01:07:13.400
And I went through the
entirety of her speech

01:07:13.400 --> 01:07:17.204
thinking she was talking
about the "frog police."

01:07:17.204 --> 01:07:19.370
Which were still doing the
same thing that the fraud

01:07:19.370 --> 01:07:22.702
police did, they were just
these 6 foot high frogs who--

01:07:22.702 --> 01:07:24.160
AMANDA PALMER:
Knocked on your door

01:07:24.160 --> 01:07:25.096
in the middle of the
night telling you

01:07:25.096 --> 01:07:26.930
that you had to get
a real fucking job.

01:07:26.930 --> 01:07:30.606
ALAN LIGHT: You
would listen to them.

01:07:30.606 --> 01:07:31.730
All right, I hate to do it.

01:07:31.730 --> 01:07:34.490
I got the signal saying I
can take one more question,

01:07:34.490 --> 01:07:36.060
so that would come
back to this side,

01:07:36.060 --> 01:07:38.360
so, sorry to the other guys.

01:07:38.360 --> 01:07:40.757
AUDIENCE: So, let's
talk about adverbs.

01:07:40.757 --> 01:07:41.590
AMANDA PALMER: Shit.

01:07:41.590 --> 01:07:42.923
AUDIENCE: Seriously, no, really.

01:07:42.923 --> 01:07:47.810
So Neil, you write a lot of
imaginative, really interesting

01:07:47.810 --> 01:07:50.620
worlds and settings,
but you rarely

01:07:50.620 --> 01:07:53.520
reuse them, or
come back to them.

01:07:53.520 --> 01:07:57.689
Do you ever miss the worlds
that you created and wish

01:07:57.689 --> 01:07:59.230
you could come back
to them, and what

01:07:59.230 --> 01:08:01.760
specific settings do
you miss the most?

01:08:01.760 --> 01:08:03.730
NEIL GAIMAN: Absolutely, I do.

01:08:03.730 --> 01:08:05.360
People think that
I have some kind

01:08:05.360 --> 01:08:08.260
of weird moral high
ground, and that I'm not

01:08:08.260 --> 01:08:10.067
the kind of writer
who does sequels,

01:08:10.067 --> 01:08:12.150
and the truth is I'm always
the kind of writer who

01:08:12.150 --> 01:08:14.840
plans to do sequels, and
would love to go back.

01:08:14.840 --> 01:08:17.689
I just get sort of--
if, on the one hand

01:08:17.689 --> 01:08:20.870
I have the choice between
something that I've done,

01:08:20.870 --> 01:08:23.859
and I know how to do it,
and I can do it well,

01:08:23.859 --> 01:08:27.920
and it now has an audience
who are waiting for more,

01:08:27.920 --> 01:08:30.974
and a publisher who will
give me more money to do it--

01:08:30.974 --> 01:08:32.640
and, on the other
hand, I have something

01:08:32.640 --> 01:08:34.740
that I have no idea
if anybody wants,

01:08:34.740 --> 01:08:37.875
that I don't know how to do,
I will always go, oh, shiny.

01:08:40.600 --> 01:08:43.000
That's what I do.

01:08:43.000 --> 01:08:51.390
Recently BBC Radio did an audio
adaptation of "Neverwhere"--

01:08:51.390 --> 01:08:52.840
BBC Radio 4.

01:08:52.840 --> 01:08:57.479
And I got to act in
it, which was amazing.

01:08:57.479 --> 01:09:01.029
Much more amazing than that
was that James McAvoy, Natalie

01:09:01.029 --> 01:09:04.060
Dormer, Sir Christopher Lee,
Bernard Cribbins, Anthony

01:09:04.060 --> 01:09:05.500
Stewart Head.

01:09:05.500 --> 01:09:09.100
The cast list is just a
who's who of amazing actors.

01:09:09.100 --> 01:09:12.210
And it goes on and on and on.

01:09:12.210 --> 01:09:15.270
And all of these
people were in it.

01:09:15.270 --> 01:09:18.819
And I got to listen to it
when they'd finished it.

01:09:18.819 --> 01:09:23.990
And I listened to the whole
six hours of BBC "Neverwhere."

01:09:23.990 --> 01:09:25.770
And I went, this is great!

01:09:25.770 --> 01:09:27.870
Why isn't there
any more of this?

01:09:27.870 --> 01:09:31.080
And then I thought, oh, it's
because I never did any more.

01:09:31.080 --> 01:09:36.420
So I went and dug out the first
page of a short story called

01:09:36.420 --> 01:09:42.180
"Hoe the Marquis Got His Coat
Back" that I started in 2002

01:09:42.180 --> 01:09:45.560
and abandoned, not
because it was bad,

01:09:45.560 --> 01:09:47.779
but because I was
writing it in a notebook

01:09:47.779 --> 01:09:50.020
that a fan had
given me with rose

01:09:50.020 --> 01:09:51.465
petals bound into the paper.

01:09:51.465 --> 01:09:52.840
And I discovered
that if you have

01:09:52.840 --> 01:09:56.600
rose petals bound into the
paper, they clog your pen.

01:09:56.600 --> 01:09:59.910
So I'd written a page and
a half and put it away.

01:09:59.910 --> 01:10:01.140
It's true.

01:10:01.140 --> 01:10:08.480
And so I finished that story and
it's 10,000, 11,000 words long.

01:10:08.480 --> 01:10:12.780
And I gave it to George R.R.
Martin and Gardner Dozois

01:10:12.780 --> 01:10:15.780
for an anthology called
"Rogues," which'll

01:10:15.780 --> 01:10:17.770
be coming out next September.

01:10:17.770 --> 01:10:21.060
And having done that,
I went, hang on,

01:10:21.060 --> 01:10:24.520
I have an entire other
"Neverwhere" novel plotted,

01:10:24.520 --> 01:10:26.992
I just never quite
got round to it.

01:10:26.992 --> 01:10:28.680
I should definitely do that.

01:10:28.680 --> 01:10:34.910
So, I really should
It's honestly

01:10:34.910 --> 01:10:36.260
not because I don't mean to.

01:10:36.260 --> 01:10:39.269
It's just, I get distracted.

01:10:39.269 --> 01:10:41.060
ALAN LIGHT: Ladies and
gentleman of Google,

01:10:41.060 --> 01:10:42.140
thank you for your time.

01:10:42.140 --> 01:10:43.640
Everybody have a lovely weekend.

01:10:43.640 --> 01:10:44.931
NEIL GAIMAN: Thank you so much.

01:10:44.931 --> 01:10:46.681
ALAN LIGHT: Neil Gaiman
and Amanda Palmer.

